ited Kingdom","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Turberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Torbet","meanings":["Scottish:","from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name <i>T(h)urbert</i>, <i>T(h)orbert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Dionysia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Denise ;   see  Dennis .  This form was in use in northern England from the 14th to the 17th century; the short form  